[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m > - [Amazon Neptune Samples](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-neptune-samples): General Neptune examples including bulk loading, Gremlin queries, and graph data modeling
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m > - [Amazon Neptune Full-Text Search with OpenSearch](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/neptune/latest/userguide/full-text-search.html): Integration pattern for combining Neptune graph queries with OpenSearch text search
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Define the graph schema.** Before loading any data, you need to define your node labels, edge types, and property keys. This isn't a formal DDL like in relational databases (Neptune is schema-free), but having a documented schema ensures consistency across your ETL pipeline and query layer. The schema defines what your graph can represent and, just as importantly, what it cannot. Skip this step and you'll end up with inconsistent property names, duplicate edge types, and queries that silently return incomplete results because someone spelled "PRACTICES_AT" as "practices_at" in one loader job.
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m // Node labels and their core properties
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m NODE Provider:
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m     npi             // National Provider Identifier (unique)
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m     first_name
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m     last_name
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m     gender
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m     accepting_new   // boolean: currently accepting new patients
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m     languages[]     // list of spoken languages
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m     board_certs[]   // list of board certifications
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m     telehealth      // boolean: offers telehealth visits
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m NODE Location:
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m     address_line1
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m     city
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m     state
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m     zip
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m     latitude
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m     longitude
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m     phone
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m     fax
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m NODE Specialty:
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m     nucc_code       // NUCC taxonomy code
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m     name            // display name (e.g., "Interventional Cardiology")
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m     category        // broad category (e.g., "Internal Medicine")
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m NODE Organization:
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m     name            // practice group or health system name
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m     type            // "practice_group", "health_system", "clinic"
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m     tax_id          // organizational TIN
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m NODE Network:
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m     network_id
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m     network_name
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m     payer_name
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m     product_type    // "HMO", "PPO", "EPO", etc.
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m NODE Facility:
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m     facility_name
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m     facility_type   // "hospital", "surgery_center", "imaging_center"
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m     cms_id          // CMS Certification Number if applicable
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m // Edge types with optional properties
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m EDGE PRACTICES_AT: Provider -> Location  (effective_date, end_date)
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m EDGE HAS_SPECIALTY: Provider -> Specialty (primary: boolean)
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m EDGE HAS_PRIVILEGES: Provider -> Facility  (privilege_type)
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m EDGE MEMBER_OF: Provider -> Organization
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m EDGE IN_NETWORK: Provider -> Network   (effective_date, term_date)
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m EDGE LOCATED_IN: Location -> Facility
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m EDGE IS_SUBSPECIALTY: Specialty -> Specialty
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m EDGE COVERS_FOR: Provider -> Provider  (coverage_type)
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Ingest and reconcile source data.** Provider data arrives from multiple systems, each with its own format and its own version of the truth. The NPI registry gives you names, taxonomy codes, and practice addresses. Credentialing systems give you privileges and board certifications. Payer rosters give you network participation. The reconciliation logic must handle conflicts (which address is current?), deduplication (is "John Smith MD" at this NPI the same as "J. Smith" in the credentialing file?), and temporal validity (this network contract expired last month). This is the hardest engineering work in the entire pipeline. Skip it and your graph will contain contradictions that produce wrong answers to patient queries.
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION ingest_provider_data(sources):
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 1: Extract raw records from each source
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m     npi_records       = parse_nppes_file(sources.npi_file)        // CMS NPPES download
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m     cred_records      = parse_credentialing_export(sources.cred)  // internal credentialing DB
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m     roster_records    = parse_payer_rosters(sources.rosters)       // 834 EDI or CSV from payers
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m     privilege_records = parse_privilege_lists(sources.privileges)  // hospital privilege files
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 2: Entity resolution. Match records across sources by NPI.
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m     // NPI is the universal key for providers. If a source lacks NPI,
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m     // fall back to name + taxonomy + address matching (Recipe 5.2 covers this in depth).
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m     unified_providers = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each npi_record in npi_records:
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m         provider = create_or_update_provider(npi_record.npi)
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m         provider.name       = npi_record.name
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m         provider.taxonomy   = npi_record.taxonomy_codes
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m         provider.addresses  = npi_record.practice_addresses
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m         unified_providers[npi_record.npi] = provider
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 3: Enrich with credentialing data (board certs, privileges)
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cred_record in cred_records:
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m         provider = unified_providers.get(cred_record.npi)
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m         IF provider exists:
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m             provider.board_certs    = cred_record.certifications
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m             provider.accepting_new  = cred_record.accepting_status
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m             provider.languages      = cred_record.languages
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 4: Add network participation from payer rosters
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each roster_record in roster_records:
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m         provider = unified_providers.get(roster_record.npi)
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m         IF provider exists:
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m             add_network_edge(provider, roster_record.network_id,
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m                            roster_record.effective_date, roster_record.term_date)
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 5: Add hospital privileges
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each priv_record in privilege_records:
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m         provider = unified_providers.get(priv_record.npi)
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m         IF provider exists:
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m             add_privilege_edge(provider, priv_record.facility_id,
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m                              priv_record.privilege_type)
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m     // Phase 6: Write reconciled data as Neptune bulk load format (CSV)
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m     write_nodes_csv(unified_providers, "providers.csv")
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m     write_edges_csv(all_edges, "edges.csv")
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN file_paths  // ready for Neptune bulk load
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Load the graph.** Neptune's bulk loader is the efficient path for initial loads and large batch updates. It reads CSV files from S3 in a specific format (node files with ~id, ~label, and property columns; edge files with ~id, ~from, ~to, ~label, and property columns). For incremental updates (a provider changes their accepting-new-patients status), use direct Gremlin or openCypher mutations rather than re-loading the entire graph. The bulk loader is idempotent for nodes (same ID overwrites), but edges need careful handling to avoid duplicates: generate deterministic edge IDs (for example, a hash of from_id + to_id + edge_label + effective_date) so that re-loading the same file doesn't create duplicate edges.
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION load_graph(node_files, edge_files, neptune_endpoint):
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m     // Upload reconciled CSV files to the Neptune load bucket
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each file in node_files + edge_files:
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m         upload_to_s3(file, bucket="neptune-load-bucket", prefix="provider-directory/")
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m     // Trigger Neptune bulk loader
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m     // The loader reads CSV from S3 and creates/updates nodes and edges
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m     load_response = call Neptune Loader API:
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m         source      = "s3://neptune-load-bucket/provider-directory/"
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m         format      = "csv"
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m         iam_role    = neptune_s3_access_role_arn
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m         region      = deployment_region
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m         mode        = "AUTO"          // creates new, updates existing
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m         failOnError = "FALSE"         // log errors, don't abort entire load
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m         parallelism = "MEDIUM"        // balance speed vs. cluster load
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m     // Monitor load status
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m     WHILE load_response.status == "LOAD_IN_PROGRESS":
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m         wait 30 seconds
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m         load_response = check_load_status(load_response.load_id)
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m     IF load_response.status == "LOAD_COMPLETED":
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m         log "Graph loaded: {node_count} nodes, {edge_count} edges"
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m         log "Load errors: review {load_response.errors_file}"
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m         // Partial loads are common. Review error file for malformed records.
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN load_response
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Build the query layer.** This is where the graph pays off. Each search request becomes a traversal that reads like the question being asked. The query layer translates application-level parameters (specialty, ZIP, network, gender, languages) into a graph traversal that starts at the most selective constraint and fans out. Query optimization matters here: starting from the network node (which connects to thousands of providers) is less efficient than starting from a specific ZIP code's geographic area (which connects to dozens of locations). The query planner should choose the narrowest entry point.
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION search_providers(params):
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m     // params: specialty, zip_code, network_id, gender, language,
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m     //         accepting_new, max_distance_miles, limit
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m     // Strategy: Start from the most selective constraint.
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m     // For most queries, geography + specialty is the narrowest entry point.
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  353, 353[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 4a: Geographic filtering (via OpenSearch or pre-computed geo edges)
[0m[49m[39m  354, 354[0m:[39m[49m     // If OpenSearch is unavailable, fall back to pre-computed ZIP-to-service-area
[0m[49m[39m  355, 355[0m:[39m[49m     // edges in Neptune. Implement a circuit breaker with a 2-second timeout so
[0m[49m[39m  356, 356[0m:[39m[49m     // an OpenSearch outage doesn't take down the entire search path.
[0m[49m[39m  357, 357[0m:[39m[49m     nearby_locations = query OpenSearch:
[0m[49m[39m  358, 358[0m:[39m[49m         filter by geo_distance(params.zip_code, params.max_distance_miles)
[0m[49m[39m  359, 359[0m:[39m[49m     location_ids = extract IDs from nearby_locations
[0m[49m[39m  360, 360[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  361, 361[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 4b: Graph traversal from locations to providers with filters
[0m[49m[39m  362, 362[0m:[39m[49m     query = START traversal:
[0m[49m[39m  363, 363[0m:[39m[49m         // Begin at locations within geographic range
[0m[49m[39m  364, 364[0m:[39m[49m         V(location_ids)
[0m[49m[39m  365, 365[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  366, 366[0m:[39m[49m         // Traverse to providers who practice at these locations
[0m[49m[39m  367, 367[0m:[39m[49m         .in("PRACTICES_AT")
[0m[49m[39m  368, 368[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  369, 369[0m:[39m[49m         // Filter: correct specialty (including subspecialties)
[0m[49m[39m  370, 370[0m:[39m[49m         .where(
[0m[49m[39m  371, 371[0m:[39m[49m             out("HAS_SPECIALTY").has("nucc_code", within(
[0m[49m[39m  372, 372[0m:[39m[49m                 get_specialty_and_subspecialties(params.specialty)
[0m[49m[39m  373, 373[0m:[39m[49m             ))
[0m[49m[39m  374, 374[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  375, 375[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  376, 376[0m:[39m[49m         // Filter: in the requested network
[0m[49m[39m  377, 377[0m:[39m[49m         .where(
[0m[49m[39m  378, 378[0m:[39m[49m             out("IN_NETWORK").has("network_id", params.network_id)
[0m[49m[39m  379, 379[0m:[39m[49m             .has("term_date", greater_than(today))  // not terminated
[0m[49m[39m  380, 380[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  381, 381[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  382, 382[0m:[39m[49m         // Filter: accepting new patients
[0m[49m[39m  383, 383[0m:[39m[49m         .has("accepting_new", true)
[0m[49m[39m  384, 384[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 385[0m:[39m[49m         // Optional filters
[0m[49m[39m  386, 386[0m:[39m[49m         IF params.gender:
[0m[49m[39m  387, 387[0m:[39m[49m             .has("gender", params.gender)
[0m[49m[39m  388, 388[0m:[39m[49m         IF params.language:
[0m[49m[39m  389, 389[0m:[39m[49m             .has("languages", containing(params.language))
[0m[49m[39m  390, 390[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  391, 391[0m:[39m[49m         // Return provider details with their locations and distance
[0m[49m[39m  392, 392[0m:[39m[49m         .project("provider", "location", "distance")
[0m[49m[39m  393, 393[0m:[39m[49m         .limit(params.limit)
[0m[49m[39m  394, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 395[0m:[39m[49m     results = execute query against Neptune
[0m[49m[39m  396, 396[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  397, 397[0m:[39m[49m     // Step 4c: Rank results (distance, then availability, then patient ratings if available)
[0m[49m[39m  398, 398[0m:[39m[49m     ranked = sort results by distance ascending
[0m[49m[39m  399, 399[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  400, 400[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN ranked
[0m[49m[39m  401, 401[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  402, 402[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION get_specialty_and_subspecialties(specialty_code):
[0m[49m[39m  403, 403[0m:[39m[49m     // Traverse the specialty hierarchy to include all subspecialties
[0m[49m[39m  404, 404[0m:[39m[49m     // "Cardiology" should match "Interventional Cardiology", "Electrophysiology", etc.
[0m[49m[39m  405, 405[0m:[39m[49m     codes = query Neptune:
[0m[49m[39m  406, 406[0m:[39m[49m         V().has("Specialty", "nucc_code", specialty_code)
[0m[49m[39m  407, 407[0m:[39m[49m         .emit()                          // include the starting node
[0m[49m[39m  408, 408[0m:[39m[49m         .repeat(in("IS_SUBSPECIALTY"))   // walk down the hierarchy
[0m[49m[39m  409, 409[0m:[39m[49m         .values("nucc_code")
[0m[49m[39m  410, 410[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN codes
[0m[49m[39m  411, 411[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  412, 412[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  413, 413[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Handle incremental updates.** The bulk load handles the initial population and periodic full refreshes. But provider data changes constantly: a provider stops accepting patients, moves to a new location, joins or leaves a network. These changes need to propagate to the graph within hours (or minutes for critical changes like network terminations). The incremental update path uses direct graph mutations rather than re-loading.
[0m[49m[39m  414, 414[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  415, 415[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  416, 416[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_incremental_update(change_event):
[0m[49m[39m  417, 417[0m:[39m[49m     // change_event contains: entity_type, entity_id, change_type, new_values
[0m[49m[39m  418, 418[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  419, 419[0m:[39m[49m     // Validate: confirm the event source is authorized and the change magnitude
[0m[49m[39m  420, 420[0m:[39m[49m     // is within expected bounds. A single event terminating 1,000 providers
[0m[49m[39m  421, 421[0m:[39m[49m     // should trigger an alert, not execute silently.
[0m[49m[39m  422, 422[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  423, 423[0m:[39m[49m     IF change_event.entity_type == "provider":
[0m[49m[39m  424, 424[0m:[39m[49m         IF change_event.change_type == "property_update":
[0m[49m[39m  425, 425[0m:[39m[49m             // Update provider properties (e.g., accepting_new changed to false)
[0m[49m[39m  426, 426[0m:[39m[49m             mutate Neptune:
[0m[49m[39m  427, 427[0m:[39m[49m                 g.V().has("Provider", "npi", change_event.entity_id)
[0m[49m[39m  428, 428[0m:[39m[49m                 .property(change_event.field, change_event.new_value)
[0m[49m[39m  429, 429[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  430, 430[0m:[39m[49m         IF change_event.change_type == "new_location":
[0m[49m[39m  431, 431[0m:[39m[49m             // Provider started practicing at a new location
[0m[49m[39m  432, 432[0m:[39m[49m             mutate Neptune:
[0m[49m[39m  433, 433[0m:[39m[49m                 g.V().has("Provider", "npi", change_event.entity_id)
[0m[49m[39m  434, 434[0m:[39m[49m                 .addE("PRACTICES_AT")
[0m[49m[39m  435, 435[0m:[39m[49m                 .to(V().has("Location", "id", change_event.location_id))
[0m[49m[39m  436, 436[0m:[39m[49m                 .property("effective_date", change_event.effective_date)
[0m[49m[39m  437, 437[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  438, 438[0m:[39m[49m         IF change_event.change_type == "network_termination":
[0m[49m[39m  439, 439[0m:[39m[49m             // Provider left a network. Update the edge term_date.
[0m[49m[39m  440, 440[0m:[39m[49m             // Do NOT delete the edge: historical network participation
[0m[49m[39m  441, 441[0m:[39m[49m             // is needed for claims adjudication lookups.
[0m[49m[39m  442, 442[0m:[39m[49m             mutate Neptune:
[0m[49m[39m  443, 443[0m:[39m[49m                 g.V().has("Provider", "npi", change_event.entity_id)
[0m[49m[39m  444, 444[0m:[39m[49m                 .outE("IN_NETWORK")
[0m[49m[39m  445, 445[0m:[39m[49m                 .has("network_id", change_event.network_id)
[0m[49m[39m  446, 446[0m:[39m[49m                 .property("term_date", change_event.term_date)
[0m[49m[39m  447, 447[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  448, 448[0m:[39m[49m     // Sync the change to OpenSearch for text/geo search consistency
[0m[49m[39m  449, 449[0m:[39m[49m     update_opensearch_index(change_event)
[0m[49m[39m  450, 450[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  451, 451[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the change for audit trail
[0m[49m[39m  452, 452[0m:[39m[49m     log_change_event(change_event)
[0m[49m[39m  453, 453[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  454, 454[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  455, 455[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3 and Neptune's openCypher endpoint, check out the [Python Example](chapter13.02-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
